Acta Oecologica

Volume 110, May 2021, 103717

Rare Pteridophytes are disproportionately frequent in the tropical forest of Xishuangbanna, Yunnan, China

Author links open overlay panelDanieleCicuzzaab
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actao.2021.103717Get rights and content

Highlights

•

130 pteridphytes assessed, with plot-based method, in tropical forest (China).

•

The 66% of the 99 terrestrial species were considered rare.

•

The 97% of the 31 epiphyte species were considered rare.

•

Rare epiphytic species, richness and cover, was higher at higher elevation.

•

Rare terrestrial species, richness and cover, was higher at lowland sites.

Abstract

The richness and cover of tropical fern life-forms — terrestrial and epiphytic — vary due to their ecology and evolutionary history. It is important to understand the responses of both terrestrial and epiphytic species in relation to topography, as elevation and other aspects, to better predict their distribution. This study has investigated the richness and cover of terrestrial and epiphytic fern species in the landscape of Xishuangbanna, Yunnan, China. The ferns were classified as either rare or common based on their occurrence and the cover values from 75 transects. A General Linear Model was created to understand the impact of the elevation and topographic aspects on the rare and common fern species. A total of 130 ferns species were found. Out of the total richness, 74% of species were considered rare and assessed as having either a narrow or a wide distribution but low frequency. The rarity increased up to 90% for the epiphytic species.

Both rare and common epiphytic species had higher richness and cover values at higher elevations. While common epiphytes had higher cover values at a high elevation in the northern aspect, the rare epiphyte species were richer at a higher elevation for both aspects. The richness and cover of the terrestrial species was negatively correlated with elevation and there was a significant interaction. Specifically, most of the rare and common terrestrial ferns were in the lowland sites of Xishuangbanna (from 600 m a.s.l.) However, only 20 species out of the total 130 species contributed to a total cover above 50% with the other species having only a minor density. Our results emphasize the high number of rare species with a low occurrence and show there to be a conservation concern in the fragmented tropical landscape of southern Yunnan.

1. Introduction

In tropical landscapes, plant species composition indicates a high disparity between common and rare species (Leita et al., 2016; Zizka et al., 2018). The proportion between common and rare species is related to their evolutionary history and environmental factors (Linder, 2019). This is particularly high and relevant in tropical habitats (Backes et al., 2019). At the geographical distribution level, species are generally considered to be rare in relation to the three characteristics of their geographic range, habitat specificity and local population size (Rabinowitz, 1981; Gaston, 1994; Gaston and Fuller, 2009). The definition of rare species includes those with small localized populations and individuals that occur at extremely low frequencies. In the tropical and subtropical habitats subset of widespread trees (Williams et al., 2017) and herbaceous species (Liu et al., 2017), they dominate over rare species which occurs with lower frequency and in a smaller distribution area.

An excellent system in which to explore the ratio between rare and common taxa and their distribution is the fern and fern allies species (hereafter called only “ferns” for simplicity). Ferns are a common taxonomic group with their peak of diversity in the tropics for both terrestrial and epiphytic life forms (Atkinson et al., 2000; Kreft and Jetz, 2007). Species diversity increases from the lowlands up towards the mountain sites with greater epiphytic species richness at higher elevations. At the continental scale, fern species distribution is primarily explained by climatic factors such as temperature and cloud cover (Khine et al., 2019) whereas at the more local scale, the fern community composition is strongly related to topography, slope and its proximity to river or humid sites (Jones et al., 2016) with the presence of given families and genera richness in species composition and cover values. Ferns are able to colonize a wide range of niches and have the ability to cope with drought due their improved hydraulic transport which avoids cavitation (Pittermann et al., 2011). Their vein and stomatal density allows for better water use efficiency (Murphy et al., 2017).

Elevation and aspect are the two environmental factors that have a great influence on the ferns and other herbaceous terrestrial and epiphytic species (Moeslund et al., 2013; Tremblay and Castro, 2009). Elevation is often correlated with an increase in air humidity which is more suitable for fern species (Karger et al., 2012). Rare species tend to increase their species richness along the elevational gradient (Bhattarai et al., 2004; Merckx et al., 2015). This is due to the increase of more suitable niches such as emerging rocks or humid habitats (Kluge and Kessler, 2011b). The northern and southern aspects, with their different microclimatic conditions, play a crucial role in fern species distribution. Ferns indicate a clear demarcation of the microclimatic partition between the drier southern aspect sites with lower richness and the contrasting humid northern aspect sites (Jones et al., 2011). Moreover, if epiphytic fern assemblages have their pick at mid-elevation, the climate acts as a filter in favor of the species that have distinct morphological traits and can cope with the local microclimatic condition (Kluge and Kessler, 2011a). Common species are often more generalist whereas rare species tend to be more specialized in their ecology and habitats (Guo et al., 2013). In some cases, they are primarily found in understory habitats (Davidar et al., 2018).

In the South-west of China, Xishuangbanna prefecture, biodiversity studies have reported that the northern aspect hills are statistically important when explaining tree richness (Liu and Slik, 2014). However, tree data poorly predicts diversity and the abundance of fern species (Pasion et al., 2018). Fern diversity in this area is different between the tropical forests with acidic soil and those with a limestone substrate with a complete turn-over of species (Phoutthavong et al., 2019). However, our understanding of the different patterns between common and rare fern species remains limited.

Understanding how the extraordinary diversity of rare species can be maintained at the local level and over a fragmented tropical forest landscape is crucial in ecological studies as well as for conservation actions. The present study is part of a larger research project that aims to document the richness of ferns and their conservation status in the tropical, human fragmented landscape of Xishuangbanna, southern Yunnan, China. The study evaluates both common and rare fern species and their life forms in relation to abiotic factors. More specifically, I asked the following questions: 1) How many rare and common ferns species occur in the Xishuangbanna prefecture? 2) Is the richness of the common and rare species different between the drier and humid sites? and 3) Is elevation and the local aspects a major player for the cover values of rare and common fern species?

2. Methods

2.1. Study area

The autonomous prefecture of Xishuangbanna is located south of Yunnan between 21° 09′N and 22° 36′N and between 99° 58′E and 101° 50′E (Fig. 1). Xishuangbanna occupies an area of 19,690 km2 comprised of mountainous and hilly terrain with the highest peak at 2429 m asl and the lowest point at 480 m asl. The seasonality was strong with a dry season from November to May and a wet season from May to October. The prefecture is crossed by the Mekong River, located in its center and running approximately from north to south. The forest vegetation was classified into four forms: tropical rain forest, tropical mountain rain forest, tropical seasonal mountain forest and tropical mountain evergreen broad-leaved forest (Hua, 2006). The southern part of the prefecture (Mengla county) has a tropical rain forest with a unique dipterocarp species, Parashorea chinensis (Dipterocarpaceae). The forests with P. chinensis are richer in species and similar to tropical SE Asian forests. In contrast, the north and north-west of the prefecture, due to an average higher elevation, has tropical mountain forests with more deciduous tree species (Hua, 2006).

2.2. Species assessment

The floristic study was conducted at 75 sites using a transect-based method. Each transect consisted of three 10 × 10 m plots with an interval of 30 m between them. The transect total length was 90 m including the plots. Within the area of Xishuangbanna prefecture the transects, when possible, were distributed homogenously (Fig. 1). In the large forest fragment, a pair of transects were repeated at an interval of 500 m along the elevation with a humid (North) and dry aspect respectively (South, South-East and South-West) whereas the medium fragments in the transect were repeated only for the humid and dry aspects. In total, 255 plots were conducted with a total of 22.500 square meters surveyed. Elevation and the coordinates were taken for each plot with a GPS and averaged for the whole transect. Within each plot, every fern species was annotated for its presence or absence. All fern species were recorded and the total cover was visually estimated with the following classes (0–1%, 1–5%, 5–10%, 10–20%, 20–40, 40–60%, 60–80% and 80–100%). The visual cover estimation for each species was conducted with an imaginary projection of all of the individuals of the species, terrestrial, climber and epiphytes alike. Subsequently it was possible to estimate the classes in relation to the plot dimensions. Individual ferns with at least one frond longer than 10 cm were recorded and epiphytic and climbing species were also included. The species were categorized according to life-form type using terrestrial and epiphyte categories. Terrestrial was defined as self and non-self-supporting, as climbers and as individuals with rhizomes in the soil. Epiphytic was defined as growing on a trunk or tree crown. Fern specimens were collected inside and outside the plot in order to have fertile material available for correct species identification. Species identification followed the flora of China (Pteridophytes) (Aa.Vv. Vol. 2–3, 2013), particularly the lycophytes and ferns of China (Zhang Xian-Chun Zhang 2012). Samples were deposited at the XTBG Herbarium (HITBC), the Sichuan University Herbarium (CDBI), Chengdu and a small collection at the Herbarium of the University of Brunei Darussalam (UBDH), Brunei Darussalam.

2.3. Data analyses

Fern species richness and cover were the two dependent variables considered in this study. Species richness consisted of the total number of species assessed in each transect and species cover was calculated using the mean of the cover value species per transect. The contributions of common and rare species to the total species richness were determined by correlating the overall richness to the richness in the subsets of species (Lennon et al., 2004). A species could be classified as rare if its distribution fit one of the three criteria: a narrow geographic range, a high habitat specificity/low occurrence or a consistently small population size (Song et al., 2015). I used only the data assessed according to the 75 transects of this study to assign rarity classes to the fern species, hereafter referred to as 'local rarity'. The species were ranked in order of increasing number. The species with only one record of their presence throughout all of the transects were considered to have a narrow distribution while those with more than one record had a wide distribution. For each distribution category, a second ranking was performed for species cover. Species with a cover index of less than 10% were considered to have low cover and species with a cover index greater than 10% were defined as having high cover (Vanderpoorten and Engels, 2003). This classification resulted in four different categories for the species’ geographic range: a wide range of distribution with high or low cover and a narrow range of distribution with high or low cover. Species were considered to be locally rare when they had a wide distribution with a low cover value and when they had a narrow distribution with low or high cover. This last category is justified because in our study area, narrow distribution with a high cover implied species that the recorded in a single site with a cover value above 10% were locally abundant but still poorly represented in the large Xishuangbanna landscape. For most of the common families and species, relative occurrence (Ro) and relative cover value (Rc) were calculated using the Ro = occurrence of the given species, specifically the total occurrence of the total species. The same method was used for the relative cover values with cover value as the units.

Furthermore, to test whether the richness of rare species per transect was correlated with the total number of species per transect, a Pearson correlation test was performed. A generalized linear model (GLM) was also performed to examine the effects of the environmental variables on the rare and common fern species richness and cover at the landscape level. For the GLM, a Poisson error distribution was used. The independent variables included in the model were elevation and aspect. Before inclusion in the model, the aspect, a circular variable expressed in degrees, was transformed with trigonometric sin (aspect) and cos (aspect) formula representing the respective northness and eastness aspects. All analyses were conducted using the R statistical software 3.5.1 with the R packages Vegan and Visreg (Oksanen, 2013).

3. Results

3.1. Taxonomic richness and composition

The total richness of the fern species in Xishuangbanna's forested landscape was of 130 species in 75 transects. Of these 130 species, 99 (76% of all species) had a terrestrial life form and the remaining 31 species (24%) had an epiphytic life form (Table 1 Add. Mat). The fern cover index, estimated per transect, varied between 1 and 100% with an average cover of 21%. The number of species per transect ranged from 1 to 14 for all ferns (Mean = 6.8 ± 2.7), from 0 to 12 for terrestrial ferns (Mean = 4.8 ± 2.0) and 0 to 6 for epiphytic species (Mean = 2.0 ± 1.2). The 130 species belonged to 46 genera and 18 families (Table 1 Add. Mat). The three richest families were Polypodiaceae, Pteridaceae and Thelypteridaceae with 20 (15%), 18 (14%) and 14 (11%) species respectively (with the total percentage in parentheses). The three most frequent species recorded were Woodwardia japonica (L. f.) Sm. (relative occurrence Ro = 7.9%, relative cover value Rc = 19.9%), Athyrium dissitifolium (Baker) C. Christensen (Ro = 6.5%, Rc = 3.6%) and Lygodium japonicum (Thunberg) Swartz (Ro = 6.3%, Rc = 2.0%), whereas the three species with the highest cover values were Woodwardia japonica (L. f.) Sm., Cibotium barometz (L.) J. Sm. (Ro = 4.0%, Rc = 16.0%) and Arachniodes cavaleriei (Christ) Ohwi (Ro = 1.7%, Rc = 5.3%). The three most frequent epiphytic species were Davallia solida (G. Foster) Swartz (Ro = 11.2%, Rc = 10.8%), Pyrrosia lanceolata (L) Farwell (Ro = 9.2%, Rc = 8.8%) and Lepisorus annamensis (C. Christensen) Li Wang (Ro = 3.1%, Rc = 6.7%).

3.2. Species rarity

The species distribution and their cover showed that out of 130 species, 73% were considered to be locally rare with our criterion of low range and a particular cover value (Table 1). The examination of the relationship between richness and rarity showed that transects with high richness also contained a high number of rare fern species (r = 0.45, p < 0.001, Fig. 2). Species with a narrow distribution and low cover represented 33% whereas those with a wide distribution (67% in total) included 40% of the species with low cover. Rare species represented 66% of terrestrial ferns and the percentage increased up to 97% for locally rare epiphytic species (Table 1). Rarity is defined here as species with a wide distribution with low cover and a narrow distribution with low or high cover. From the 18 total families, 14 were locally rare species. Polypodiaceae and Pteridaceae made up 21% and 27% of the rare species respectively. Among the terrestrial rare species, Pteridaceae and Thelypteridaceae made up 20% and 15% of the total rare species respectively. The situation was drastically different for the rare epiphytic species represented by only three families. Polypodiaceae totaled 19 rare species, representing 63% of the total rarity of epiphytic species.

3.3. Effects of elevation and aspect on species richness and cover

The epiphytic fern richness of common species showed a positive increase with elevation, whereas the model showed that the number of rare epiphytic species increased with elevation and in the dry and humid aspects. Terrestrial rare and common species had a negative trend with elevation. The total richness showed an interaction between elevation and the other aspects with a positive trend whereas the total richness of the common species had a negative trend with elevation (Table 2, Fig. 3). Moving to the cover values of the fern species, we observed that common and rare epiphytes have a positive trend with elevation, increasing their cover values in both dry and humid sites. The cover of rare terrestrial species has a negative pattern with elevation whereas for the common terrestrial species, the cover values decreased along the elevation as well for the drier and humid sites. To conclude, the cover value of all rare species increased with elevation whereas the total cover of common species decreased along the elevation, as observed in dry and humid sites (Table 2).

4. Discussion

4.1. Fern species and rarity

The study reports that the majority of ferns species in the forest habitat of Xishuangbanna Prefecture are locally rare. Two-thirds of terrestrial species are rare whereas nearly all epiphytes are rare. Spatially, the rare species are more frequent at higher elevations with the driest sites being slightly richer in terms of the epiphytes and the total number of species. Furthermore, the species cover shows that for terrestrial species, there is a decrease along the elevation with higher values at the lowland sites. Common epiphytes increase along the elevation occurring at the north and south sites (Table 2). Overall, most of the species (73%) have a narrow or wide distribution but low cover values, showing that the fern species in Xishuangbanna Prefecture tend to have a population size characterized by low cover and few individuals. The epiphytic life forms that were considered locally rare reached 97%. Two-thirds of these species have a wide distribution (collected in more than one transect) with low abundance.

4.2. Fern species’ elevation and topographic aspects

In this study, the elevation ranges from 603 m asl to 2020 m asl. Epiphytic species both rare and common are significantly more abundant at higher elevations, therefore, epiphytic ferns are particularly concentrated in the sub-mountain and mountain forests of Xishuangbanna (Hua, 2006). This could be explained by the increase in the number of suitable niches for the fern species such as in ravines or humid habitats (Kluge and Kessler, 2011b). The common patterns demonstrate that the richness and cover of the terrestrial species is not random but significantly higher at the lowland sites in contrast to the results of other studies (Kessler et al., 2010). The high richness in low elevation sites is also confirmed for the woody species as trees (Pasion et al., 2018). Although ferns are often more dominant in sub-montane and montane forests where the humidity levels are high (Cardelus et al., 2006), this study found that terrestrial species are more abundant in sites between 600 and 900 m asl either in the north and south aspects. Even if the study area experiences a dry season, in lowland sites, the presence of dense fog in the morning compensates for the decrease in rain for the species that can retain a rather large proportion of water through leaf absorption (Fu et al., 2016). Moreover, the total biomass of the fern species is primarily produced by a small proportion of the total species richness (Axmanová et al., 2012). Just 34 of the common species, only 26% of the total richness, have a total abundance that is four times higher than the total of all of the rare species’ abundance together. Therefore the abundance and ultimately, the fern biomass, are the result of approximately a quarter of the total species richness. Epiphytes on the other hand are richer along the elevation of the Xishuangbanna landscape. In fact, epiphytes tend to have higher richness and cover values in the northern and more humid sites compared with the dry southern sites (Fig. 3, Table 2). This shows that rare species have an ecological niche in humid sites, therefore they have less physiological stress and are able to expand their populations via sexual or vegetative reproduction (Zhang et al., 2014).

It is important to note that in tropical plant ecology, a high number of species are recorded once in the plot or transect-based method. For example, in the Amazonian basin, 23% of terrestrial ferns species have been recorded once (Tuomisto, Hanna, Ruokolainen, 1993). For trees species in Borneo, out of over 230 species, 27 were recorded once, 43 twice and 23 and 16 three and four times respectively (Sheil et al., 2010). Beside Parashorea chinensis, other species have the southern part of Yunnan as their northern area of distribution as they are mainly centered in South East Asia (Hua, 2006). However, the species at this latitude tend to decrease their density and become rare (Cai et al., 2019; Liu et al., 2019). Therefore, it can be concluded that the high level of rarity among the ferns species is the combination of the ecological aspects as well as the northern limit distribution of many species recorded in this study.

5. Conclusion

The fern flora in China includes 2244 species (Yue-Hong Yan et al., 2013) whereas the Chinese red list of higher plants reports 28 families of ferns and lycophytes in danger of extinction, including 183 species classified as vulnerable to endangered (Dong et al., 2017; Qin et al., 2017). Rare species are not invariably threatened by imminent extinction, therefore it is important to delimit the threatened and rare species and to not use these categories as synonyms (Gaston, 2012). This study reports that 74% of the total forest species are considered to be locally rare, rising to 97% if we consider only the epiphytes. This low level of occurrence is due to the interaction of several aspects such as habitat specificity, local ecological condition and species distribution. This highlights that the high rarity is mirrored by the different functional traits able to colonize dry and humid sites of the sub-mountain forest landscape. It is important to peruse further study into the species with a low level of occurrence in order to understand their morphological, physiological and genetic differences from those population in their center of distribution (Liu et al., 2019). This is urgent in terms of the prediction of a climate change scenario for the region.

Moreover, the expansion of rubber plantations in Xishuangbanna has evolved from the lowlands to a higher elevation (Kou et al., 2018), even inside protected areas (Jin and Fan, 2018) with forests set aside in the northern aspect sites that harbour high tree species diversity and high fern species abundance (Liu and Slik, 2014). However, rare epiphytic species occur also in the southern mountain sites with high richness and a low level of occurrence. Unfortunately, these sites have already been affected by the rubber expansion. In conclusion, an ecological study is important not only to consider the major woody plant community but also to include the neglected groups with low occurrence that considerably contribute to plant richness.
